




TY  - JOUR
T1  - How Strong Are Bequest Motives? Evidence Based on Estimates of the Demand for Life Insurance and Annuities
AU  - Bernheim, B. Douglas
Y1  - 1991/10/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261783
DO  - 10.1086/261783
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 899
EP  - 927
VL  - 99
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper presents new empirical evidence in support of the view that a significant fraction of total saving is motivated by the desire to leave bequests. Specifically, I find that social security annuity benefits significantly raise life insurance holdings and depress private annuity holdings among elderly individuals. These patterns indicate that the typical household would choose to maintain a positive fraction of its resources in bequeathable forms, even if insurance markets were perfect. Evidence on the relationship between insurance purchases and total resources reinforces this conclusion.
AB  - This paper presents new empirical evidence in support of the view that a significant fraction of total saving is motivated by the desire to leave bequests. Specifically, I find that social security annuity benefits significantly raise life insurance holdings and depress private annuity holdings among elderly individuals. These patterns indicate that the typical household would choose to maintain a positive fraction of its resources in bequeathable forms, even if insurance markets were perfect. Evidence on the relationship between insurance purchases and total resources reinforces this conclusion.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261783
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261783
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Full Insurance in the Presence of Aggregate Uncertainty
AU  - Mace, Barbara J.
Y1  - 1991/10/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261784
DO  - 10.1086/261784
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 928
EP  - 956
VL  - 99
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper tests implications of full consumption insurance. The object is to determine how much mileage can be obtained from a model with complete markets, with such features as private information or liquidity constraints omitted. The implication exploited is that individual consumption responds to aggregate risk but not to idiosyncratic risk. The test involves regressing the change in household consumption onto the change in aggregate consumption and other right-hand-side variables such as the change in household income and change in employment status. All variables other than the change in aggregate consumption are predicted to be insignificant in explaining the change in household consumption. With observations on consumption and income for 10,695 households from the Consumer Expenditure Survey, the results are mixed. The results for one specification (exponential utility) are mostly consistent with full consumption insurance; the results for the other specification (power utility) are not.
AB  - This paper tests implications of full consumption insurance. The object is to determine how much mileage can be obtained from a model with complete markets, with such features as private information or liquidity constraints omitted. The implication exploited is that individual consumption responds to aggregate risk but not to idiosyncratic risk. The test involves regressing the change in household consumption onto the change in aggregate consumption and other right-hand-side variables such as the change in household income and change in employment status. All variables other than the change in aggregate consumption are predicted to be insignificant in explaining the change in household consumption. With observations on consumption and income for 10,695 households from the Consumer Expenditure Survey, the results are mixed. The results for one specification (exponential utility) are mostly consistent with full consumption insurance; the results for the other specification (power utility) are not.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261784
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261784
Y2  - 2024/03/22
